onial rule.Clancy-Smith demonstrates the continuities between the eras of Turkish and French rule as well as the importance of regional ties among elite families in defining Saharan political cultures. She rejects the position that Algerians and Tunisians were invariably victims of western colonial aggression, arguing instead that Muslim notables understood the outside world and were quite capable of manipulating the massive changes occurring around them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIslam and politicszAlgeria. 0aIslam and politicszTunisia. 0aSufisxPolitical activityzAlgeria. 0aSufisxPolitical activityzTunisia. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  a1849 bu ziyan uprising.  aaccommodation.  aafrica.  aafrican history.  aalgeria.  abaraka.  abarud.  acolonial rule.  acolonialism.  acomparative studies on muslim societies.  acultural studies.  acultural survival.  aemigration.  afrench colonialism.  aislam.  ajihad.  amuslim elites.  amuslim.  anorth african history.  apolitical actions.  apopulism.  aprotest.  areligion.  areligious beliefs.  aresistance.  asaharan political cultures.  atunisia.  aturkish colonialism.  awestern colonial aggression.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021216940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520920378?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520920378/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY